      "content": "Modern historians would likely see the critique of the UN as both legitimate and reflective of broader systemic issues. The UN's structure, particularly the veto power held by the five permanent members of the Security Council, often leads to paralysis in the face of major conflicts. This power imbalance means that the UN can be seen as a victim of the geopolitical realities of the world, where the interests of the big powers often overshadow collective action. While the UN has had some successes, its inability to prevent major wars or address global issues effectively highlights the need for reform to make it a more effective and representative institution.",
